sec.p:
New xenophyophores (Foraminifera, 
Monothalamea
) from the eastern Clarion-Clipperton Zone (equatorial Pacific)

Since the publication of 

monograph, and particularly with the more recent advent of largescale photographic surveys of the ocean floor (

), it has become increasingly apparent that xenophyophores constitute a major part of the megafauna in many deep-sea settings. These giant agglutinated foraminifera are particularly common on seamounts and continental slopes, in submarine canyons, and on abyssal plains (

; 

; 

; 

). In the equatorial Pacific, they are a dominant group among the megafauna seen in seabed images across large areas of the Clarion-Clipperton Zone (
CCZ
), where they often outnumber all the metazoan megafauna combined (

; 

; 

, 

; 

; 

). Although xenophyophores are typically the most common organisms visible on the deep ocean floor, they are difficult to incorporate into ecological studies. Particular problems in the case of data derived from photographic surveys include the estimation of biomass and the need to distinguish living from dead specimens (

; 

). Nevertheless, they remain an important taxon, not least for their contribution to habitat structure and megafaunal biodiversity (Gooday 
et al
., 2020d; 2021).

The CCZ has attracted a lot of attention because it hosts extensive seafloor deposits of polymetallic nodules that are rich in valuable metals and hence of great commercial importance. Since this vast area lies beyond national jurisdictions, licences for exploration and prospecting are issued to state-sponsored companies and other entities that are interested in exploiting these resources by the International Seabed Authority (ISA), a United Nations body. This in turn has generated a considerable body of research aimed at better understanding the functioning and biodiversity of seabed biological communities before any commercial mining begins. The research effort has focused particularly on the eastern CCZ and has included work on the xenophyophores. These giant foraminifera have proved to be particularly diverse, with 24 new species having been described, two known species identified, and a further 39 undescribed species recognised (
, 2020d, 2021). Another five hitherto unrecognised morphotypes were recently found in epibenthic sledge material from five areas in the eastern CCZ (
). Here, we extend these studies with a survey of xenophyophore diversity in samples collected with a box core in the Ocean Mining Singapore (OMS) and Seabed Resources Limited (UK-1) license area during February and March 2020 .

